  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency WASH assistance for internally displaced people in Eastern Ghouta and Afrin displacement sites</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project will provide life-saving WASH support to people displaced from Eastern Ghouta, and Afrin in coordination with other actors. With access to displacement sites in critical need of WASH facilities in both Rural Damascus and northern Aleppo through the Ministry of Local Administration (MoLA) and Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour (MoSAL), DRC stands ready to begin activities for this project as soon as it is funded. The immediate basic needs on ground for internally displaced persons (IDPs), as reported through the WASH sector includes latrines, showers, and sanitation. The targeted beneficiary populations are living in collective shelters with little or no existing WASH infrastructure in place. Latrines and showers will be rapidly installed to: prevent the outbreak of life-endangering diseases including cholera, tetanus, and typhoid protect the privacy and safety in the collective shelters address the medical needs of people from Eastern Ghouta who have been wearing the same clothes for over one month and alleviate psycho-social distress caused by defection/urination in the open and inability to clean oneself. The project accords with the WASH sector&#x2019;s emergency WASH strategy providing safe living conditions for people displaced from Eastern Ghouta/Afrin including the provision of a minimum emergency standard of 1 latrine per 100 people and provision of garbage bins (200 litres per bin serving 20 families). It will together with the interventions of other actors create a safe environment for other humanitarian activities in the sectors of education and child protection to be delivered. Project locations will remain flexible to enable DRC to respond to the most critical needs expected sites are in Harjeleh, Adra, Nashabiyeh, Dweir, and Al-Karmak in Rural Damascus, and within Nobbol and Zahra in Aleppo. All activities will take place within collective shelters.</narrative>
  </description>
